SIMPLE: inflame
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inflame
<hw>In*flame"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inflamed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Inflaming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>enflamen</ets>, OF. <ets>enflamer</ets>, F. <ets>enflammer</ets>,
L. <ets>inflammare</ets>, <ets>inflammatum</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets>
in + <ets>flammare</ets> to flame, fr. <ets>flamma</ets> flame. See
<er>Flame</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To set on fire; to kindle; to
cause to burn, flame, or glow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We should have made retreat⟦br⟧
By light of the <qex>inflamed</qex> fleet.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To kindle or intensify, as passion or
appetite; to excite to an excessive or unnatural action or heat; <as>as,
to <ex>inflame</ex> desire</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though more, it seems,⟦br⟧
<qex>Inflamed</qex> with lust than rage.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But, O <qex>inflame</qex> and fire our hearts.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To provoke to anger or rage; to exasperate; to
irritate; to incense; to enrage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It will <qex>inflame</qex> you; it will make you mad.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To put in a state of inflammation;
to produce morbid heat, congestion, or swelling, of; <as>as, to
<ex>inflame</ex> the eyes by overwork</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To exaggerate; to enlarge upon.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A friend exaggerates a man's virtues, an enemy <qex>inflames</qex>
his crimes.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To provoke; fire; kindle; irritate; exasperate;
incense; enrage; anger; excite; arouse.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inflame</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Inflame
<hw>In*flame"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow morbidly hot,
congested, or painful; to become angry or incensed.</def>
<rj><au>Wiseman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inflamed</ent>⟦br⟧
